SENATE BILL 281
R2, B1 6lr1360
CF 6lr1359
By: Senators Augustine and Feldman
Introduced and read first time: January 20, 2026
Assigned to: Budget and Taxation
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Metro Funding Modification Act of 2026
3 FOR the purpose of requiring the Governor to withhold a certain percentage of the annual
4 appropriation for grants to the Washington Suburban Transit District under certain
5 circumstances; altering the calculation of the amount that the Governor is required
6 to include in the annual State budget each year to provide grants to the Washington
7 Suburban Transit District to pay the capital costs of the Washington Metropolitan
8 Area Transit Authority; requiring the Governor to include an appropriation in the
9 annual State budget bill for the purpose of paying the State’s proportionate share of
10 the Metrorail Operating Subsidy Allocation Formula; requiring the Department to
11 withhold certain grants for any fiscal year in which the Authority invests in a rail
12 signaling system without reaching certain collective bargaining agreements; making
13 this Act contingent on enactment of certain legislation by the Commonwealth of
14 Virgina and the District of Columbia; and generally relating to funding for the
15 Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority.
16 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
17 Article – Transportation
18 Section 10–205(f) and (g)
19 Annotated Code of Maryland
20 (2020 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
21 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
22 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
23 Article – Transportation
24 10–205.
25 (f) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) of this subsection, the Governor
26 shall include an appropriation in the annual budget of at least the amount specified in
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *sb0281*

2 SENATE BILL 281
1 paragraph (4) of this subsection for the sole purpose of providing grants to the Washington
2 Suburban Transit District to pay the capital costs of the Washington Metropolitan Area
3 Transit Authority.
4 (2) (i) The Governor is not required to make the appropriation under
5 paragraph (1) of this subsection in a fiscal year unless the Department certifies to the
6 Governor in writing before the beginning of the immediately preceding fiscal year that the
7 Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority has submitted to the Department:
8 1. Performance and condition assessments and reports
9 regarding:
10 A. The safety and reliability of rapid heavy rail and bus
11 systems;
12 B. The financial performance of the Washington
13 Metropolitan Area Transit Authority as it relates to rail and bus operations, including fare
14 box recovery, service per rider, and cost per service hour;
15 C. The monthly ridership of rail and bus systems broken
16 down by Metrorail station, Metrorail line, bus route, and bus line;
17 D. Strategies to reduce costs and improve the Washington
18 Metropolitan Area Transit Authority’s operational efficiency; and
19 E. The comparison of annual capital investments and
20 approved budgets; and
21 2. The Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority’s:
22 A. Annual budget;
23 B. Annual independent financial audit;
24 C. Annual National Transit Database profile; and
25 D. Single audit reports issued in accordance with the
26 Uniform Administrative Requirements, Cost Principles, and Audit Requirements for
27 Federal Awards under 2 C.F.R. Part 200.
28 (ii) If the Commonwealth of Virginia or the District of Columbia
29 reduce the amount of dedicated capital funding for the Washington Metropolitan Area
30 Transit Authority, the Governor may reduce the appropriation under paragraph (1) of this
31 subsection by a proportional amount.
32 (iii) 1. The Governor shall withhold 35% of the appropriation
33 under paragraph (1) of this subsection if:

SENATE BILL 281 3
1 A. The Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority has
2 received a modified audit opinion as a result of an annual independent audit conducted in
3 accordance with Article XVI, Section 70 of the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit
4 Authority Compact under § 10–204 of this subtitle; and
5 B. The Department has not certified to the Governor in
6 writing before the beginning of the immediately preceding fiscal year that the Washington
7 Metropolitan Area Transit Authority has submitted in writing to the board of directors of
8 the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority and the Maryland General Assembly
9 a satisfactory corrective plan that addresses the reasons for the modified audit opinion.
10 2. The Governor shall release the portion of the
11 appropriation withheld under subsubparagraph 1 of this subparagraph if the Washington
12 Metropolitan Area Transit Authority submits in writing to the board of directors of the
13 Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the
14 State Government Article, the Maryland General Assembly a satisfactory corrective action
15 plan that addresses the reasons for the modified audit opinion.
16 3. ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2028, THE BOARD OF
17 DIRECTORS OF THE WASHINGTON METROPOLITAN AREA TRANSIT AUTHORITY
18 SHALL APPROVE A RAIL SIGNALING AND AUTOMATION WORKFORCE TRANSITION
19 PLAN, DEVELOPED IN CONSULTATION WITH AFFECTED COLLECTIVE BARGAINING
20 UNITS.
21 4. THE GOVERNOR SHALL WITHHOLD 35% OF THE
22 APPROPRIATION UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION FOR ANY FISCAL
23 YEAR IN WHICH:
24 A. THE REQUIREMENT OF SUBSUBPARAGRAPH 3 OF
25 THIS SUBPARAGRAPH IS NOT MET; OR
26 B. A RAIL OR BUS OPERATOR EMPLOYED BY THE
27 WASHINGTON METROPOLITAN AREA TRANSIT AUTHORITY ON OR AFTER JULY 1,
28 2028, IS TERMINATED DUE TO A REDUCTION IN FORCE CAUSED BY THE AUTOMATION
29 OF THE RAIL SYSTEM.
30 (3) The Governor shall make the appropriation under paragraph (1) of this
31 subsection from the Transportation Trust Fund.
32 (4) [(i)] For the first fiscal year in which the mandated appropriation
33 under this subsection applies, the appropriation under paragraph (1) of this subsection
34 shall equal at least the amount appropriated in the fiscal year 2019 State budget as enacted
35 for the Washington Suburban Transit District to pay the capital costs of the Washington
36 Metropolitan Area Transit Authority.

4 SENATE BILL 281
1 [(ii) For each fiscal year after the first fiscal year in which the
2 mandated appropriation under this subsection applies, the appropriation under paragraph
3 (1) of this subsection shall be equal to the amount of the appropriation for the preceding
4 fiscal year increased by 3%.]
5 (g) (1) (I) The Governor shall include in the State budget an appropriation
6 for the purposes specified under [paragraph (2) of this subsection of $167,000,000]
7 PARAGRAPHS (2) AND (4) OF THIS SUBSECTION from the revenues available for the
8 State capital program in the Transportation Trust Fund.
9 (II) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2029 AND EACH FISCAL YEAR
10 THEREAFTER, FROM THE REVENUES AVAILABLE FOR THE STATE CAPITAL
11 PROGRAM, THE GOVERNOR SHALL INCLUDE IN THE STATE BUDGET AN
12 APPROPRIATION FOR THE PURPOSES SPECIFIED UNDER PARAGRAPH (4) OF THIS
13 SUBSECTION EQUAL TO THE AMOUNT AS ADJUSTED UNDER PARAGRAPH (5) OF THIS
14 SUBSECTION.
15 (2) The Department shall provide an annual grant of at least $167,000,000
16 to the Washington Suburban Transit District to be used only to pay the capital costs of the
17 Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority.
18 (3) The [grant] GRANTS required under [paragraph (2)] PARAGRAPHS
19 (2) AND (4) of this subsection [is] ARE in addition to the appropriation required under
20 subsection (f)(1) of this section.
21 (4) (I) FOR FISCAL YEAR 2029 AND EACH FISCAL YEAR
22 THEREAFTER, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL PROVIDE AN ANNUAL GRANT OF AT LEAST
23 $150,000,000 ADJUSTED AS REQUIRED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OF THIS
24 PARAGRAPH FOR THE STATE’S PROPORTIONATE SHARE OF THE METRORAIL
25 OPERATING SUBSIDY ALLOCATION FORMULA.
26 (II) FOR EACH FISCAL YEAR AFTER FISCAL YEAR 2029, THE
27 APPROPRIATION UNDER THIS PARAGRAPH SHALL BE EQUAL TO THE AMOUNT OF
28 THE APPROPRIATION FOR THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING FISCAL YEAR INCREASED
29 BY 3%.
30 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That:
31 (a) Section 1 of this Act is contingent on:
32 (1) the Commonwealth of Virginia enacting legislation that provides
33 dedicated capital funding for the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority that
34 includes:

SENATE BILL 281 5
1 (i) a mandatory appropriation for the Commonwealth of Virginia’s
2 proportionate share of the Metrorail Operating Subsidy Allocation Formula; and
3 (ii) an annual 3% increase to the mandatory appropriation; and
4 (2) the District of Columbia enacting legislation that provides dedicated
5 capital funding for the Washington Metropolitan Area Transit Authority that includes:
6 (i) a mandatory appropriation for the District of Columbia’s
7 proportionate share of the Metrorail Operating Subsidy Allocation Formula; and
8 (ii) an annual 3% increase to the base amount of capital funding.
9 (b) The Department of Transportation shall notify the Department of Legislative
10 Services in writing within 5 days after both the Commonwealth of Virginia and the District
11 of Columbia have enacted legislation that meets the requirements of subsection (a) of this
12 section.
13 (c) Section 1 of this Act shall take effect on the date that the Department of
14 Legislative Services receives notice under subsection (b) of this section.
15 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, subject to Section 2 of this
16 Act, this Act shall take effect June 1, 2026.

